{{see|extrême}}
==English==

===Etymology===
{{L.}} ''[[extremus]]'', the superlative of ''[[exterus]]''<!--should this be "externus", which means "outside"?-->

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Of a place, the most [[remote]], [[farthest]] or [[outermost]].
#:''At the '''extreme''' edges, the coating is very thin.''
# In the [[greatest]] or [[highest]] [[degree]]; [[intense]].
#:''He has an '''extreme''' aversion to needles, and avoids visiting the doctor.''
# [[Excessive]], or [[far]] [[beyond]] the [[norm]].
#:''His '''extreme''' love of model trains showed in the rails that criscrossed his entire home.''
# [[Drastic]], or of great [[severity]].
#:''I think the new laws are '''extreme''', but many believe them necessary for national security.''
# Of sports, [[difficult]] or [[dangerous]]; performed in a [[hazardous]] [[environment]].
#:''Television has begun to reflect the growing popularity of '''extreme''' sports such as bungee jumping and skateboarding.''
# (''archaic'') [[Ultimate]], [[final]] or [[last]].

====Synonyms====
*(''place''): [[far]]thest, [[furthest]], most [[distant]], [[outermost]], [[remote]]st
*(''in greatest or highest degree''): [[great]]est, [[high]]est
*(''excessive''): [[excessive]], too [[much]]
*(''drastic''): [[drastic]], [[severe]]
*(''sports''): [[dangerous]]
*(''ultimate''): [[final]], [[last]], [[ultimate]]

====Antonyms====
*(''place''): [[close]]st, [[near]]est
*(''in greatest or highest degree''): [[least]]
*(''excessive''): [[moderate]], [[reasonable]]
*(''drastic''): [[moderate]], [[reasonable]]

